**Step 8: Write code for your Discord bot**

Here is an example of how you can write a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that has one command: ban:
```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');

const client = new Client({
  intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.Messages],
  partials: ['MESSAGE', 'CHANNEL', 'GUILD']
});

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

client.on('messageCreate', (message) => {
  if (message.content === '!ban') {
    if (message.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      const member = message.mentions.members.first();
      if (member) {
        member.ban();
        message.reply(`Banned ${member.user.tag}!`);
      } else {
        message.reply('Please mention a member to ban!');
      }
    } else {
      message.reply('You don\'t have permission to ban members!');
    }
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```
Replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with the token you grabbed in step 7.

**Step 9: Set up your bot as a slash command**

To set up your bot as a slash command, you'll need to create an interaction command in the Discord developer portal. Click on "Commands" in the left sidebar and then click on "Create Command". Give your command a name, description, and the URL of your bot's script (e.g. `http://localhost:3000/bot.js`). Make sure to set the type to "Slash Command".

**Step 10: Run your bot**

Save your code and run your bot using Node.js:

```
node bot.js
```
Your bot should now be online and responding to the "!ban" command.

Note: Make sure to replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual bot token, and adjust the code as needed to fit your specific use case.

